# 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Method Overriding — Formal Definition

**Method Overriding** is a core feature of Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) in Java that allows a **subclass (child class)** to provide a *specific implementation* of a method that has *already been declared* in its **superclass (parent class)**. The overridden method in the child class must share the **exact same name**, **return type (or a covariant subtype)**, and **parameter list** as the method in the parent class.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Syllabus Definition:** *Method overriding is a runtime polymorphism mechanism in which a subclass redefines an inherited method to provide a more specialized behavior, while preserving the same method signature as defined in the superclass.*

### Conceptual Analogy

Think of a **generic form template** used in a government office. The master template has a field called "Documents Required." Now, different counters (license counter, passport counter, Aadhaar counter) all inherit this template, but each **overrides** the "Documents Required" field with their own specific list.

- The **form name** (method name) stays the same.
- The **field structure** (signature) stays the same.
- But the **content** (implementation) is specialized by the **counter** (subclass).

So when an applicant (the program) walks up to a counter and asks, "What documents do I need?", the answer depends on **which counter (actual object)** they approach — not on the type of "counter" label they were given. This is **dynamic dispatch**.

---

## 1.2 The `super` Keyword — Formal Definition

The **`super`** keyword in Java is a **reference variable** that always refers to the **immediate parent class object**. It is used to differentiate between the members of the superclass and the subclass when both have the same name.

> [!NOTE]
> **`super` is NOT a reference to "the parent class"** — it is a reference to the *parent portion of the current object*, because every child object internally contains a parent sub-object.

### Three Primary Uses of `super`

1. **`super.memberVariable`** — Access parent class instance variable when hidden by a same-named child class variable.
2. **`super.method()`** — Invoke parent class method when overridden by a child class method.
3. **`super()` or `super(args)`** — Explicitly call parent class constructor (no-arg or parameterized) from child class constructor.

### Conceptual Analogy

Imagine you are a **Junior Engineer** in a company. The company has a standard "Project Submission" form designed by the **Senior Engineer (parent class)**. When you (the subclass) need to submit, you:
- Use **`super.formTemplate()`** to get the original template from your senior.
- Then add your own section to it (extension).
- Or replace the "Remarks" section with your own customized version (overriding + super).

`super` is essentially a **time-machine back to the parent class**.

---

## 1.3 I/O Basics — Formal Definition

**I/O (Input/Output)** in Java refers to the mechanism of **reading data from a source** (keyboard, file, network socket) and **writing data to a destination** (console, file, network). The Java I/O framework is built on the concept of **streams** — ordered sequences of data flowing between source and destination.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Two Stream Hierarchies in `java.io`:**
> - **Byte Streams** — handle raw binary data, 8-bit bytes. Roots: `InputStream` and `OutputStream`.
> - **Character Streams** — handle 16-bit Unicode characters. Roots: `Reader` and `Writer`.

### Conceptual Analogy

A **stream** is like a **water pipe**. The **source** is the tank, the **destination** is the bucket, and the pipe carries the water (data). In Java:
- An **`InputStream`** is a pipe that *pours water into your program* (read).
- An **`OutputStream`** is a pipe that *pours water out of your program* (write).
- **Byte streams** carry *raw* water (binary data), while **character streams** carry *filtered, human-readable* water (text).

The **three standard streams** in Java are pre-installed pipes:
- `System.in` — pipe from the **keyboard** into your program.
- `System.out` — pipe from your program to the **console (normal output)**.
- `System.err` — pipe from your program to the **console (error output)**.

---

## 1.4 Bolded Key Terms Summary

- **Method Overriding** — Redefining an inherited method in the subclass.
- **super Keyword** — Reference to the immediate parent class object.
- **Stream** — A sequence of data flowing between source and destination.
- **Byte Stream** — 8-bit raw data I/O (`InputStream` / `OutputStream`).
- **Character Stream** — 16-bit Unicode text I/O (`Reader` / `Writer`).
- **Standard Streams** — `System.in`, `System.out`, `System.err`.
- **Dynamic Method Dispatch** — Runtime decision on which overridden method to invoke.
- **Covariant Return Type** — Subclass override returning a subtype of the original return type.

<!-- SECTION_1_END -->

<!-- SECTION_2_START -->
# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Reference Sheet

## 2.1 Method Overriding — Operational Mechanics

### Step-by-Step Mechanism

1. **Inheritance Must Exist** — Method overriding can only happen within an **IS-A relationship** (extends or implements).
2. **Method Signature Must Match** — The method in the child class must have an **identical name** and **parameter list** to the parent class method.
3. **Return Type Compatibility** — Return type must be **exactly the same** OR a **covariant subtype** (a subclass of the original return type).
4. **Access Modifier Constraint** — The overriding method **cannot be more restrictive** than the overridden method.
5. **Exception Constraint** — The overriding method can throw **fewer or narrower checked exceptions**, but **no new or broader checked exceptions**.
6. **Static and Final Methods** — `static` methods are **hidden** (not overridden), and `final` methods **cannot be overridden at all**.
7. **Constructor Rule** — Constructors **cannot be overridden** (they are not inherited).
8. **Invocation Mode** — A call like `parentRef.method()` is resolved at **compile time** (based on reference type) but executed at **runtime** (based on actual object type). This is **Dynamic Method Dispatch** — the heart of runtime polymorphism.

### Why is Overriding Needed?

- **Specialization** — The child class can provide behavior specific to its type while sharing a common interface.
- **Runtime Polymorphism** — Enables loose coupling and flexible design.
- **Open/Closed Principle** — Open for extension, closed for modification (a SOLID OOP principle).

---

## 2.2 The `super` Keyword — Detailed Analysis

### Three Usage Scenarios

| Use Case | Syntax | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| Parent class variable | `super.variableName` | Access hidden parent variable |
| Parent class method | `super.methodName(args)` | Invoke overridden parent method |
| Parent class constructor | `super()` or `super(args)` | Chain to parent constructor |

### Critical Rule: Constructor Chaining

> [!IMPORTANT]
> If a constructor **does not explicitly call** `super()` or `this()`, the Java compiler **automatically inserts** a call to the **no-argument constructor** of the parent class as the **first statement**. If the parent class does not have a no-arg constructor, a **compilation error** occurs.

The flow is:
1. `main()` invokes `Child(args)`.
2. **First line** of child constructor calls `super(args)` (or implicitly `super()`).
3. Parent class constructor runs, initializing inherited members.
4. Control returns to the child constructor, which then initializes its own members.

This guarantees that **inherited members are always initialized before the child-specific members** — preventing the use of uninitialized inherited fields.

---

## 2.3 Java I/O Stream Architecture

### Byte Stream Hierarchy (Top → Bottom)

- `java.io.InputStream` (abstract)
  - `FileInputStream` — reads raw bytes from a file
  - `BufferedInputStream` — adds buffering for performance
  - `DataInputStream` — reads Java primitives in a machine-independent way
  - `ObjectInputStream` — used for deserialization
- `java.io.OutputStream` (abstract)
  - `FileOutputStream` — writes raw bytes to a file
  - `BufferedOutputStream` — adds buffering
  - `DataOutputStream` — writes Java primitives
  - `PrintStream` — `System.out` and `System.err` are instances

### Character Stream Hierarchy

- `java.io.Reader` (abstract)
  - `FileReader` — reads characters from a file
  - `BufferedReader` — adds buffering, supports `readLine()`
  - `InputStreamReader` — bridge from byte stream to character stream
- `java.io.Writer` (abstract)
  - `FileWriter` — writes characters to a file
  - `BufferedWriter` — adds buffering
  - `OutputStreamWriter` — bridge from character stream to byte stream
  - `PrintWriter` — convenient `print()`/`println()` methods

### Byte vs. Character Streams — When to Use

| Feature | Byte Stream | Character Stream |
|---|---|---|
| Data Unit | 8-bit byte | 16-bit Unicode char |
| Best For | Binary data (images, audio, PDF) | Text data (TXT, CSV, JSON) |
| Performance | Faster for binary | Optimized for Unicode text |
| Encoding Handling | Manual | Automatic (uses default charset) |

---

## 2.4 KTU High-Yield Reference Sheet (Method Overriding + super + I/O)

| **Element** | **Syntax / Rule** | **Key Constraint** |
|---|---|---|
| Override method signature | `access_modifier return_type methodName(params)` | Must match parent name + parameter list exactly |
| Covariant return | Override return can be a subtype | E.g., parent returns `Object`, child may return `String` |
| Access modifier | Cannot be more restrictive | `protected` → `public` ✓ ; `public` → `private` ✗ |
| Final methods | Cannot be overridden | Compile-time error |
| Static methods | Hidden, not overridden | Determined at compile time |
| super variable | `super.fieldName` | Refers to parent's field |
| super method | `super.methodName(args)` | Must be valid parent method |
| super constructor | `super()` or `super(args)` | Must be first line; auto-inserted if missing |
| Byte stream | `InputStream` / `OutputStream` | 8-bit data, raw binary |
| Character stream | `Reader` / `Writer` | 16-bit Unicode text |
| Standard input | `System.in` (InputStream) | Connected to keyboard by default |
| Standard output | `System.out` (PrintStream) | Connected to console by default |
| Standard error | `System.err` (PrintStream) | Connected to console by default |
| BufferedReader method | `readLine()` | Reads one line at a time, returns `String` |
| Scanner method | `nextInt()`, `nextLine()` | Parses tokens from input |

---

## 2.5 Real-World Engineering Utility

- **Method Overriding** is the foundation of **plugin architectures** (e.g., Java Servlets: `HttpServlet.doGet()` is overridden in user code).
- **`super`** enables **template method design pattern** and is essential in **framework development** (Spring, Android SDKs).
- **Java I/O** is the backbone of **file processing systems**, **log analyzers**, **network servers**, **data pipelines**, and **compiler file readers**. Mastering byte/character streams is essential for **data engineering** and **system programming** roles.
<!-- SECTION_2_END -->

<!-- SECTION_3_START -->
# 3. Step-by-Step Derivations, Code Walkthroughs & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Method Overriding — Complete Walkthrough with Java Program

### Code Listing 1: Method Overriding Demonstrating Runtime Polymorphism

```java
// File: ShapeDemo.java
class Shape {
    void draw() {
        System.out.println("Drawing a generic shape");
    }

    double area() {
        return 0.0;
    }
}

class Circle extends Shape {
    double radius;

    Circle(double radius) {
        this.radius = radius;
    }

    @Override
    void draw() {
        System.out.println("Drawing a circle with radius " + radius);
    }

    @Override
    double area() {
        return Math.PI * radius * radius;
    }
}

class Rectangle extends Shape {
    double length, breadth;

    Rectangle(double length, double breadth) {
        this.length = length;
        this.breadth = breadth;
    }

    @Override
    void draw() {
        System.out.println("Drawing a rectangle " + length + " x " + breadth);
    }

    @Override
    double area() {
        return length * breadth;
    }
}

public class ShapeDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Step 1: Compile-time reference is Shape, but runtime object is Circle
        Shape s1 = new Circle(5.0);
        Shape s2 = new Rectangle(4.0, 6.0);

        // Step 2: At compile time, Java checks if 'draw()' exists in Shape (it does).
        // At runtime, the JVM checks the actual object type and calls the
        // overridden version.
        s1.draw();   // Calls Circle.draw()
        s2.draw();   // Calls Rectangle.draw()

        // Step 3: Polymorphic method call for area()
        System.out.println("Area of shape 1: " + s1.area());
        System.out.println("Area of shape 2: " + s2.area());
    }
}
```

### Line-by-Line Logical Breakdown

**Step 1 — Declaration of `Shape s1 = new Circle(5.0);`**
- Compile time: Java verifies that `Shape` has the methods being called later. Reference type is `Shape`.
- Runtime: The actual object in memory is a `Circle`. The JVM stores the actual class metadata.

**Step 2 — Call `s1.draw();`**
- The compiler resolves the call against the `Shape` class (where `draw()` is defined).
- The JVM, at runtime, looks at the actual object's class (`Circle`), finds its `draw()` method, and invokes **that** version.
- This is the essence of **Dynamic Method Dispatch**.

**Step 3 — Call `s1.area();`**
- The same dispatch logic applies. The reference is `Shape`, but the call is routed to `Circle.area()` or `Rectangle.area()` based on the actual object.

### Output

```
Drawing a circle with radius 5.0
Drawing a rectangle 4.0 x 6.0
Area of shape 1: 78.53981633974483
Area of shape 2: 24.0
```

---

## 3.2 The `super` Keyword — Exhaustive Demonstration

### Code Listing 2: super for Variables, Methods, and Constructors

```java
// File: EmployeeDemo.java
class Employee {
    String name = "Generic Employee";
    double salary = 30000;

    Employee() {
        System.out.println("Parent Employee constructor called");
    }

    Employee(String name) {
        this.name = name;
        System.out.println("Parent Employee parameterized constructor called");
    }

    void display() {
        System.out.println("Name: " + name + ", Salary: " + salary);
    }
}

class Manager extends Employee {
    String name = "Default Manager";   // Hides parent 'name'

    int teamSize;

    Manager() {
        // Step 1: Implicit super() call would go here if not overridden
        super();  // Explicit call to parent no-arg constructor
        System.out.println("Child Manager default constructor called");
    }

    Manager(String name, int teamSize) {
        // Step 2: Call parent's parameterized constructor
        super(name);
        this.teamSize = teamSize;
        System.out.println("Child Manager parameterized constructor called");
    }

    void display() {
        // Step 3: Call parent's display() first, then add child-specific info
        super.display();
        System.out.println("Team Size: " + teamSize);
    }

    void showNames() {
        // Step 4: Access both parent and child 'name' variables
        System.out.println("Child name   : " + this.name);
        System.out.println("Parent name  : " + super.name);
    }
}

public class EmployeeDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Manager m1 = new Manager();             // Calls no-arg chain
        System.out.println("---");
        Manager m2 = new Manager("Alice", 10);  // Calls parameterized chain
        System.out.println("---");

        m2.display();      // Uses super.display() + child addition
        System.out.println("---");
        m2.showNames();    // Demonstrates super.name vs this.name
    }
}
```

### Step-by-Step Execution Trace

**Execution of `new Manager()`:**
1. JVM pushes `Manager()` onto the call stack.
2. **First line** of `Manager()` is `super()` → calls `Employee()` (parent no-arg constructor).
3. `Employee()` runs: prints `Parent Employee constructor called`.
4. Control returns to `Manager()`. Prints `Child Manager default constructor called`.

**Execution of `new Manager("Alice", 10)`:**
1. JVM calls `Manager("Alice", 10)`.
2. **First line** is `super("Alice")` → calls `Employee(String name)`.
3. `Employee(String)` sets `name = "Alice"` and prints `Parent Employee parameterized constructor called`.
4. Control returns. `this.teamSize = 10` is executed. Prints `Child Manager parameterized constructor called`.

**Execution of `m2.display()`:**
1. `display()` is called on `Manager` object.
2. First line is `super.display()` → calls `Employee.display()`. Prints `Name: Alice, Salary: 30000.0`.
3. After returning, prints `Team Size: 10`.

**Execution of `m2.showNames()`:**
1. `this.name` refers to the child's `name` field: `"Default Manager"`.
2. `super.name` refers to the parent's `name` field: `"Alice"` (set via super("Alice")).

### Output

```
Parent Employee constructor called
Child Manager default constructor called
---
Parent Employee parameterized constructor called
Child Manager parameterized constructor called
---
Name: Alice, Salary: 30000.0
Team Size: 10
---
Child name   : Default Manager
Parent name  : Alice
```

---

## 3.3 Java I/O Basics — Reading and Writing Files

### Code Listing 3: Reading a Text File Using `FileReader` and `BufferedReader`

```java
// File: ReadFileDemo.java
import java.io.BufferedReader;
import java.io.FileReader;
import java.io.IOException;

public class ReadFileDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Step 1: Use try-with-resources to ensure the stream is auto-closed
        try (BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new FileReader("input.txt"))) {
            String line;
            // Step 2: readLine() returns null when EOF is reached
            while ((line = br.readLine()) != null) {
                System.out.println(line);
            }
        } catch (IOException e) {
            System.out.println("Error reading file: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}
```

### Step-by-Step Logical Walkthrough

**Step 1 — Stream Construction**
- `FileReader("input.txt")` opens a character stream connected to the file.
- `BufferedReader(br)` wraps the reader, adding an internal buffer (typically 8192 characters) for efficient reading.

**Step 2 — Reading Loop**
- `br.readLine()` reads one line at a time, including the line separator stripping.
- Returns `null` at end-of-file (EOF) — the loop terminates.
- The `try-with-resources` statement automatically calls `br.close()` when the block exits (normally or via exception).

**Step 3 — Exception Handling**
- `IOException` is the checked superclass for all I/O failures (file not found, permission denied, etc.).

---

### Code Listing 4: Writing to a Text File Using `FileWriter` and `BufferedWriter`

```java
// File: WriteFileDemo.java
import java.io.BufferedWriter;
import java.io.FileWriter;
import java.io.IOException;

public class WriteFileDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String[] lines = {
            "Line 1: Hello, KTU students!",
            "Line 2: Object Oriented Programming.",
            "Line 3: Java I/O is essential."
        };

        try (BufferedWriter bw = new BufferedWriter(new FileWriter("output.txt"))) {
            for (String line : lines) {
                bw.write(line);
                bw.newLine();  // Platform-independent line separator
            }
            System.out.println("File written successfully.");
        } catch (IOException e) {
            System.out.println("Error writing file: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}
```

### Step-by-Step Logical Walkthrough

**Step 1 — Stream Construction**
- `FileWriter("output.txt")` opens a character stream for writing. By default, this **overwrites** the file.
- `BufferedWriter(bw)` adds an internal buffer. Data is flushed to the file when the buffer is full, when `flush()` is called, or when `close()` is invoked.

**Step 2 — Writing Data**
- `bw.write(line)` writes the string to the buffer.
- `bw.newLine()` writes the platform-independent line separator (`\n` on Unix, `\r\n` on Windows).

**Step 3 — Resource Management**
- The `try-with-resources` block guarantees `bw.close()` is called, which flushes any remaining buffered data to the file and releases OS resources.

---

### Code Listing 5: Reading User Input from the Console Using `Scanner`

```java
// File: UserInputDemo.java
import java.util.Scanner;

public class UserInputDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // System.in is an InputStream (byte stream)
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);

        System.out.print("Enter your name: ");
        String name = sc.nextLine();

        System.out.print("Enter your age: ");
        int age = sc.nextInt();

        System.out.println("Hello " + name + ", you are " + age + " years old.");

        sc.close();  // Always close Scanner to release System.in
    }
}
```

### Step-by-Step Logical Walkthrough

**Step 1 — `Scanner` Initialization**
- `new Scanner(System.in)` wraps the byte stream `System.in` and parses it into tokens of various types.

**Step 2 — Token Extraction**
- `sc.nextLine()` reads characters until a newline and returns them as a `String`.
- `sc.nextInt()` reads and parses the next token as an `int`.

**Step 3 — Resource Cleanup**
- `sc.close()` is important because `Scanner` reads from `System.in`, which if left open, prevents the JVM from exiting cleanly.

---

## 3.4 Analytical Matrix — When to Use What?

| **Scenario** | **Recommended Class** | **Stream Type** | **Reason** |
|---|---|---|---|
| Read text file line by line | `BufferedReader` wrapping `FileReader` | Character | `readLine()` convenience, efficient buffering |
| Write text to file | `BufferedWriter` wrapping `FileWriter` | Character | Efficient buffered text output |
| Read raw binary (image) | `FileInputStream` | Byte | Avoids charset conversion issues |
| Write raw binary | `FileOutputStream` | Byte | Preserves bit-exact data |
| Read from keyboard (complex) | `Scanner` | Byte (wrapped) | Easy token parsing |
| Read from keyboard (single char) | `BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(System.in))` | Character | Line-based input |
| Print formatted output | `System.out.printf()` | Byte (PrintStream) | Built-in format specifiers |
| Append to existing file | `FileWriter(path, true)` | Character | Second `true` argument enables append mode |

---

## 3.5 Dynamic Method Dispatch — Bytecode-Level Insight

> [!NOTE]
> The JVM uses a **virtual method table (vtable)** to resolve overridden method calls at runtime.
>
> - Each class loaded into the JVM has a **vtable** mapping method signatures to actual method implementations.
> - When a method is overridden, the child's entry **replaces** the parent's entry in the vtable.
> - When `s1.draw()` is compiled, the bytecode contains an instruction like `invokevirtual Shape.draw()`.
> - At runtime, the JVM looks up the vtable of the **actual object's class** (Circle), retrieves the address of `Circle.draw()`, and invokes it.
> - This is why overriding is **zero-overhead** at the call site (just a vtable lookup).

```
Compile-time binding (reference type Shape)  →  bytecode: invokevirtual Shape.draw
Runtime binding (actual object Circle)      →  vtable lookup → Circle.draw()
```

