# 4. Structural Diagrams & Schematics

## 4.1 Mermaid Diagram — Dynamic Method Dispatch Flow

```mermaid
graph TD
    A1[Code: parentRef.childMethod] --> B1[Compiler: Check parent class]
    B1 --> C1{Does method exist in parent type?}
    C1 --> D1[Compilation Error]
    C1 --> E1[Code Compiles Successfully]
    E1 --> F1[JVM: Runtime Phase]
    F1 --> G1[Identify actual object class]
    G1 --> H1[Look up method in vtable]
    H1 --> I1{Is method overridden?}
    I1 --> J1[Execute parent version]
    I1 --> K1[Execute child overridden version]
```

**Explanation of the flow:**
- **Step A1 → B1:** The compiler inspects the *reference type* (not the object type) to check whether the method call is legal.
- **Step C1:** If the method does not exist in the reference type, the code fails to compile.
- **Step E1 → F1:** Once compiled, the bytecode contains an `invokevirtual` instruction.
- **Step F1 → G1:** At runtime, the JVM examines the actual object on the heap.
- **Step H1 → I1:** The vtable of the actual class is consulted.
- **Step I1 → J1 / K1:** The JVM invokes the appropriate version — the parent's if no override exists, the child's if overridden.

---

## 4.2 Mermaid Diagram — Java I/O Class Hierarchy

```mermaid
graph TD
    A1[java.io Package] --> B1[Byte Streams]
    A1 --> B2[Character Streams]
    A1 --> B3[Standard Streams]

    B1 --> C1[InputStream Abstract]
    B1 --> C2[OutputStream Abstract]

    C1 --> D1[FileInputStream]
    C1 --> D2[BufferedInputStream]
    C1 --> D3[DataInputStream]
    C1 --> D4[ObjectInputStream]

    C2 --> D5[FileOutputStream]
    C2 --> D6[BufferedOutputStream]
    C2 --> D7[DataOutputStream]
    C2 --> D8[PrintStream]

    B2 --> C3[Reader Abstract]
    B2 --> C4[Writer Abstract]

    C3 --> D9[FileReader]
    C3 --> D10[BufferedReader]
    C3 --> D11[InputStreamReader]

    C4 --> D12[FileWriter]
    C4 --> D13[BufferedWriter]
    C4 --> D14[OutputStreamWriter]
    C4 --> D15[PrintWriter]

    B3 --> E1[System.in - InputStream]
    B3 --> E2[System.out - PrintStream]
    B3 --> E3[System.err - PrintStream]
```

**Explanation:**
- The **root** of byte I/O is `InputStream` (for reading) and `OutputStream` (for writing).
- The **root** of character I/O is `Reader` and `Writer`.
- **Standard streams** are pre-defined static fields in the `System` class — `System.in`, `System.out`, `System.err`.
- The **decorator pattern** is heavily used: e.g., `BufferedReader` wraps a `FileReader` to add buffering on top of file reading.

---

## 4.3 Mermaid Diagram — Constructor Chaining with `super()`

```mermaid
graph TD
    A1[main calls new Child args] --> B1[Child constructor invoked]
    B1 --> C1{Does Child have super or this call as first line?}
    C1 --> D1[Compiler auto-inserts super]
    C1 --> D2[Explicit super or this present]
    D1 --> E1[Parent no-arg constructor runs]
    D2 --> F1{super or this?}
    F1 --> G1[super args - Parent parameterized constructor runs]
    F1 --> H1[this args - Another Child constructor runs]
    G1 --> I1[Control returns to Child constructor]
    E1 --> I1
    H1 --> I1
    I1 --> J1[Child-specific initialization executes]
    J1 --> K1[Constructor returns to main]
```

**Explanation:**
- This flow enforces the rule that **parent class members are always initialized before child class members**.
- If neither `super()` nor `this()` is explicitly written, the compiler silently inserts `super()`.
- If the parent lacks a no-arg constructor, this implicit insertion becomes a **compilation error**.

---

## 4.4 Mermaid Diagram — Buffered I/O Workflow

```mermaid
graph LR
    A1[Source File] -->|raw bytes| B1[FileInputStream]
    B1 -->|raw bytes| C1[BufferedInputStream]
    C1 -->|bulk reads| D1[Java Program]
    D1 -->|bulk writes| E1[BufferedOutputStream]
    E1 -->|raw bytes| F1[FileOutputStream]
    F1 -->|raw bytes| G1[Destination File]
```

**Explanation:**
- Direct file I/O (without buffering) is **slow** because each `read()` or `write()` triggers a system call.
- `BufferedInputStream` / `BufferedOutputStream` accumulate data in memory and perform **fewer, larger I/O operations** — typically 5–10x faster for small reads/writes.
- This is the **Decorator Pattern** in action — `BufferedInputStream` decorates `FileInputStream` with extra functionality.
