**(b) [7 Marks]** Explain the Java I/O class hierarchy. Differentiate between byte streams and character streams with examples.

**Model Solution:**

**Java I/O Class Hierarchy (3 marks):**

The `java.io` package provides two parallel hierarchies for I/O operations:

1. **Byte Stream Hierarchy** — Built on `InputStream` and `OutputStream` abstract classes.
   - `InputStream` subclasses: `FileInputStream`, `BufferedInputStream`, `DataInputStream`, `ObjectInputStream`
   - `OutputStream` subclasses: `FileOutputStream`, `BufferedOutputStream`, `DataOutputStream`, `PrintStream` (used by `System.out` and `System.err`)

2. **Character Stream Hierarchy** — Built on `Reader` and `Writer` abstract classes.
   - `Reader` subclasses: `FileReader`, `BufferedReader`, `InputStreamReader`
   - `Writer` subclasses: `FileWriter`, `BufferedWriter`, `OutputStreamWriter`, `PrintWriter`

3. **Standard Streams** — Static fields of `java.lang.System`:
   - `System.in` (type `InputStream`)
   - `System.out` (type `PrintStream`)
   - `System.err` (type `PrintStream`)

**Byte Streams vs Character Streams (4 marks):**

| Feature | Byte Streams | Character Streams |
|---|---|---|
| Data unit | 8-bit bytes | 16-bit Unicode characters |
| Abstract root | `InputStream` / `OutputStream` | `Reader` / `Writer` |
| Best for | Binary data (images, audio, executables) | Text data (TXT, JSON, XML) |
| Encoding handling | No conversion | Uses default charset (UTF-8) |
| Performance for text | Slower, may misread multibyte chars | Faster and correct for Unicode |
| Example classes | `FileInputStream`, `FileOutputStream` | `FileReader`, `FileWriter` |

**Example (byte stream):**
```java
FileInputStream fis = new FileInputStream("image.png");
int b;
while ((b = fis.read()) != -1) {
    // process each byte
}
fis.close();
```

**Example (character stream):**
```java
FileReader fr = new FileReader("notes.txt");
int c;
while ((c = fr.read()) != -1) {
    System.out.print((char) c);
}
fr.close();
```

For **text I/O**, character streams are always preferred because they correctly handle Unicode and platform-specific encodings.

