# 📗 SECTION 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Reference

## 2.1 Anatomy of the `Scanner` Class

The `Scanner` class (introduced in **Java 5 / JDK 1.5**) is a simple text scanner that can parse primitive types and strings using **regular expressions**.

### Class Hierarchy

```text
java.lang.Object
   └── java.util.Scanner
       (implements Iterator<String>)
```

### Construction

```java
Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
```

- It takes a `Readable` source (here, `System.in`).
- It uses **whitespace** as the default delimiter (splits input on spaces, tabs, newlines).

### Most-Used Methods (The "Cheat Sheet" You Must Memorize)

| Method | Return Type | Purpose / Use-Case |
|--------|-------------|-------------------|
| `next()` | `String` | Reads a single **word** (up to whitespace) |
| `nextLine()` | `String` | Reads the **entire line** (until `\n`) |
| `nextInt()` | `int` | Reads a single integer token |
| `nextDouble()` | `double` | Reads a single floating-point token |
| `nextFloat()` | `float` | Reads a single float token |
| `nextLong()` | `long` | Reads a long integer token |
| `nextBoolean()` | `boolean` | Reads `true` or `false` |
| `next().charAt(0)` | `char` | Reads a single character (via `String`) |
| `hasNextInt()` | `boolean` | Verifies if next token is an int (validation) |
| `hasNextLine()` | `boolean` | Verifies if another line exists |
| `close()` | `void` | Releases the underlying stream |

### Custom Delimiters

```java
sc.useDelimiter(",");   // split input on commas
sc.useDelimiter("\\|"); // split on pipe character
```

## 2.2 The `BufferedReader` Class

`BufferedReader` is part of the **character-stream I/O** hierarchy in `java.io`. It reads text from a character-input stream, **buffering characters** to provide efficient reading of characters, arrays, and lines.

### Why Use `BufferedReader` Instead of `Scanner`?

> [!NOTE]
> **Performance Reality Check:** `BufferedReader` is approximately **8x faster** than `Scanner` for large input volumes. This is critical in **competitive programming** and **production server applications** where speed matters.

The reason: `Scanner` performs **regex parsing** on every token, which is heavy. `BufferedReader` only buffers raw characters with minimal overhead.

### Standard Construction Pattern

```java
BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(System.in));
String line = br.readLine();
```

To parse integers, you must **manually convert** the String:

```java
int n = Integer.parseInt(br.readLine().trim());
```

## 2.3 The `Console` Class (For Secure Input)

`Console` is used to read password-like input where character **echoing is disabled**.

```java
Console c = System.console();
char[] password = c.readPassword("Enter password: ");
```

> [!WARNING]
> **`System.console()` returns `null`** when run from an IDE like Eclipse, IntelliJ, or NetBeans because they don't allocate a real console. It only works from a true terminal (CMD, Bash, PowerShell).

## 2.4 Critical Pitfall: The `nextLine()` Trap 🪤

> [!WARNING]
> **The #1 Reason Students Lose Marks in KTU Labs:**
> When you call `nextInt()`, `nextDouble()`, etc., the scanner reads the **number** but **leaves the newline character (`\n`) in the buffer**. The very next `nextLine()` call consumes this leftover `\n` and returns an **empty string**, breaking your program logic.

**Solution:** Add an extra `sc.nextLine();` (a "dummy" call) after every numeric read to consume the leftover newline.

## 2.5 Command-Line Arguments (An Alternative "Input" Method)

Java also accepts input via the `main` method's `String[] args` parameter:

```java
public static void main(String[] args) {
    String name = args[0];
    int age = Integer.parseInt(args[1]);
}
```

- Passed at runtime: `java MyProgram Rahul 21`
- Useful for **scripts, automation, and CI/CD pipelines**.

