## 3.4 Worked Example 3: Validation Using `hasNext*()` Methods

**Problem:** Repeatedly ask the user for an integer between 1 and 100 until valid input is provided.

```java
import java.util.Scanner;

public class ValidatedInput {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
        int num = 0;
        boolean valid = false;

        while (!valid) {
            System.out.print("Enter an integer (1-100): ");
            if (sc.hasNextInt()) {
                num = sc.nextInt();
                if (num >= 1 && num <= 100) {
                    valid = true;
                } else {
                    System.out.println("Out of range! Try again.");
                }
            } else {
                System.out.println("That's not an integer! Try again.");
                sc.next();   // discard the invalid token
            }
        }
        System.out.println("You entered: " + num);
        sc.close();
    }
}
```

## 3.5 Worked Example 4: `BufferedReader` for High-Volume Input

**Problem:** Read `N` integers from a single line separated by spaces and print their sum.

```java
import java.io.*;

public class SumBuffered {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {
        BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(System.in));

        System.out.print("Enter N: ");
        int n = Integer.parseInt(br.readLine().trim());

        System.out.print("Enter " + n + " numbers separated by spaces: ");
        String[] tokens = br.readLine().trim().split("\\s+");

        int sum = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            sum += Integer.parseInt(tokens[i]);
        }
        System.out.println("Sum = " + sum);
    }
}
```

## 3.6 Comparison Table: `Scanner` vs `BufferedReader`

| Feature | `Scanner` | `BufferedReader` |
|---------|-----------|------------------|
| Package | `java.util` | `java.io` |
| Parsing built-in | ✅ Yes (`nextInt`, etc.) | ❌ No (manual `parseInt`) |
| Speed (1M lines) | ~3.5 sec | ~0.4 sec |
| Thread-safe | ❌ No | ✅ Yes (synchronized) |
| Regex/Delimiter | ✅ Yes | ❌ No |
| Read whole line | `nextLine()` | `readLine()` |
| Buffer size | 1 KB (default) | 8 KB (default) |
| Closes automatically | Only on `System.in` if no other refs | No — must `close()` |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU One-Liner to Remember:** *"Scanner is for **simplicity**, BufferedReader is for **speed**."*

