## 🅰️ PART A — Short Answer Questions (2 × 3 = 6 Marks)

### **Q1. [KTU University Exam – May 2024]**
**Explain the role of the `System.in` object in Java. Why is it not directly used for reading user input in most programs?**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

`System.in` is a static final field of the `java.lang.System` class, representing the **standard input stream** that is automatically connected to the keyboard when a Java program starts. It is an instance of `java.io.InputStream`, meaning it operates at the **byte level** and can only return raw integer values (0–255) representing bytes.

It is not directly used because:
1. It reads **raw bytes**, not typed values like `int`, `double`, or `String`, requiring tedious manual conversion.
2. It has no built-in method to read an entire line of text.
3. It is unbuffered and inefficient for large input.

Therefore, higher-level classes like `Scanner` or `BufferedReader` are wrapped around `System.in` to provide convenient, type-safe, and efficient input operations. **(3 marks)**

