## 🅱️ PART B — Long Answer Questions (Module Internal Choice Pattern)

### ✅ **Question A (14 Marks)** [Choice 1]

> **[KTU University Exam – May 2024 Model Question]**

**(a)** Write a Java program that reads an employee's name, employee ID (integer), and monthly salary (double) from the console and displays them. Explain each step in your program. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** What is the `nextLine()` trap in Java's `Scanner` class? Demonstrate it with a program and show how to fix it. **(7 marks)**

---

#### 🔹 Solution to Q.A(a):

```java
import java.util.Scanner;

public class Employee {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);

        // Step 1: Read String input using nextLine()
        System.out.print("Enter employee name: ");
        String name = sc.nextLine();

        // Step 2: Read integer input using nextInt()
        System.out.print("Enter employee ID: ");
        int id = sc.nextInt();

        // Step 3: Read double input using nextDouble()
        System.out.print("Enter monthly salary: ");
        double salary = sc.nextDouble();

        // Step 4: Display formatted output
        System.out.println("\n--- Employee Details ---");
        System.out.println("Name   : " + name);
        System.out.println("ID     : " + id);
        System.out.println("Salary : Rs. " + salary);

        sc.close();
    }
}
```

**Explanation of each step:**
1. `import java.util.Scanner;` imports the Scanner class.
2. `new Scanner(System.in)` creates a Scanner bound to the standard input.
3. `nextLine()` reads the full name (handles spaces).
4. `nextInt()` parses the next whitespace-delimited token as an `int`.
5. `nextDouble()` parses the next token as a `double`.
6. `sc.close()` releases the underlying input stream. **(7 marks — full)**

---

#### 🔹 Solution to Q.A(b):

**The `nextLine()` Trap:**
When `nextInt()`, `nextDouble()`, etc. are called, they read only the numeric characters and **leave the newline character (`\n`) in the input buffer**. The very next call to `nextLine()` reads this leftover newline and returns an **empty string**, causing the program to behave unexpectedly.

**Demonstration of the Bug:**

```java
import java.util.Scanner;

public class TrapDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);

        System.out.print("Enter roll number: ");
        int roll = sc.nextInt();        // reads the number; leaves \n

        System.out.print("Enter full name: ");
        String name = sc.nextLine();    // ❌ BUG: reads the leftover \n

        System.out.println("Roll: " + roll + ", Name: '" + name + "'");
        // Output: Roll: 21, Name: ''   (name is EMPTY)
        sc.close();
    }
}
```

**Fix — Consume the leftover newline:**

```java
import java.util.Scanner;

public class TrapFix {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);

        System.out.print("Enter roll number: ");
        int roll = sc.nextInt();
        sc.nextLine();                  // ✅ CONSUMES the leftover \n

        System.out.print("Enter full name: ");
        String name = sc.nextLine();    // ✅ Now correctly reads "Rahul Kumar"

        System.out.println("Roll: " + roll + ", Name: " + name);
        sc.close();
    }
}
```

**(7 marks — full)**

