### ✅ **Question B (14 Marks)** [Choice 2]

> **[KTU University Exam – Dec 2023 Model Question]**

**(a)** Compare and contrast the `Scanner` class and the `BufferedReader` class for reading console input. Mention the package, performance, parsing capability, and thread-safety of each. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Write a Java program using `BufferedReader` to read `N` integers from a single space-separated line and print their sum and average. **(7 marks)**

---

#### 🔹 Solution to Q.B(a):

| Feature | `Scanner` | `BufferedReader` |
|---------|-----------|------------------|
| **Package** | `java.util` | `java.io` |
| **Parsing** | Built-in (`nextInt`, `nextDouble`, etc.) | Not built-in; requires `Integer.parseInt()` etc. |
| **Performance** | Slower (uses regex parsing on every read) | **8x faster** (buffered char array, no regex) |
| **Thread-safe** | ❌ Not thread-safe | ✅ Synchronized methods, thread-safe |
| **Buffer Size** | 1 KB | 8 KB |
| **Delimiter** | Customizable via `useDelimiter()` | Cannot change (only newline-based via `readLine()`) |
| **Best For** | Beginners, small programs, mixed-type reads | Large-volume input, competitive programming, production code |
| **Construction** | `new Scanner(System.in)` | `new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(System.in))` |

**Conclusion:** Use `Scanner` for **simplicity and quick prototyping**. Use `BufferedReader` for **high-performance, large-scale, or thread-safe** input. **(7 marks — full)**

---

#### 🔹 Solution to Q.B(b):

```java
import java.io.*;

public class SumAverage {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {
        BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(System.in));

        // Step 1: Read N
        System.out.print("Enter N: ");
        int n = Integer.parseInt(br.readLine().trim());

        // Step 2: Read N space-separated integers
        System.out.print("Enter " + n + " integers separated by spaces: ");
        String[] tokens = br.readLine().trim().split("\\s+");

        // Step 3: Compute sum
        long sum = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            sum += Integer.parseInt(tokens[i]);
        }

        // Step 4: Compute average as double
        double average = (double) sum / n;

        // Step 5: Display results
        System.out.println("Sum     = " + sum);
        System.out.println("Average = " + average);

        br.close();
    }
}
```

**Sample Run:**

```
Enter N: 4
Enter 4 integers separated by spaces: 10 20 30 40
Sum     = 100
Average = 25.0
```

**Explanation of key lines:**
- `new InputStreamReader(System.in)` — converts byte stream to character stream.
- `br.readLine().trim()` — reads line and removes leading/trailing whitespace.
- `.split("\\s+")` — splits on one or more whitespace characters.
- `Integer.parseInt(tokens[i])` — manually converts String token to int.
- `(double) sum / n` — cast to `double` to get floating-point average. **(7 marks — full)**

