## 🧠 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

- ✅ **`System.in`** is a static `InputStream` connected to the keyboard — it reads **bytes**, not characters.
- ✅ **`Scanner`** (from `java.util`) is the **easiest** class for console input — it has built-in methods: `nextInt()`, `nextDouble()`, `nextLine()`, `next()`, `hasNextInt()`, etc.
- ✅ **`next()`** reads a **single word**; **`nextLine()`** reads the **entire line** until `\n`.
- ✅ The **whitespace delimiter** is the default tokenizer for `Scanner`.
- ✅ **`BufferedReader`** (from `java.io`) is **faster but requires manual parsing** using `Integer.parseInt()`, `Double.parseDouble()`, etc.
- ✅ Always wrap `System.in` with `InputStreamReader` before passing to `BufferedReader`.
- ✅ The **`nextLine()` trap** is the **#1 bug** when mixing `nextInt()` and `nextLine()` — fix it by adding a dummy `sc.nextLine()` call.
- ✅ The **`Console`** class is used for **secure password input** (no echo) and only works in a real terminal — `null` in IDEs.
- ✅ **Closing the scanner** (`sc.close()`) is good practice to release OS resources.
- ✅ **Command-line arguments** (`String[] args`) provide an alternative non-interactive input method for scripts and automation.
- ✅ **Performance rule of thumb:** `BufferedReader` > `Scanner` for > 10⁵ lines of input.
- ✅ **Thread-safety:** `BufferedReader` is synchronized (thread-safe); `Scanner` is **not** thread-safe.

