# MODULE 3 — THE `private` ACCESS SPECIFIER IN OBJECT-ORIENTED PROGRAMMING

## 1.1 Formal Academic Definition

In the paradigm of **Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)**, the keyword **`private`** is an **access specifier** (also called an *access modifier* or *visibility label*) that enforces the highest level of **data hiding** within a class. When a class member—either a data member (attribute/variable) or a member function (method)—is declared under the `private` visibility region, its accessibility is **strictly restricted to the class in which it is defined**.

Formally, as per the **KTU 2024 Scheme (NEP 2020 aligned) OOP syllabus**:

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Definition:** A `private` member of a class is accessible **only** by the member functions and `friend` entities of that **same class**. It is **not accessible** by objects of the class directly, nor by any derived (child) class, nor by any external code outside the class.

The `private` keyword is one of three canonical access specifiers in classical OOP languages such as **C++** (alongside `public` and `protected`). It is the cornerstone mechanism for implementing the OOP principle of **Encapsulation**.

| Visibility Level | Keyword | Access Scope |
|---|---|---|
| **Lowest (most restrictive)** | `private` | Same class only |
| **Intermediate** | `protected` | Same class + derived classes |
| **Highest (least restrictive)** | `public` | Everywhere (universal) |

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy — The Bank Locker System

> [!NOTE]
> **Intuition (Bank Locker Analogy):** Imagine you have a **personal bank locker** at a bank branch.
>
> - **YOU** (the locker owner / class itself) → can open it freely. ✅
> - The **Bank Manager with the master key** (`friend` function) → can open it. ✅
> - Your **Son/Daughter with a joint access card** (derived class) → ❌ **Cannot open it** (unless given explicit permission via `protected` or a public method).
> - A **random stranger on the street** (external object / main function) → ❌ **Absolutely cannot open it.**
>
> The locker contents are **`private`** to you. The locker mechanism enforces this rule rigidly.

This analogy directly maps to how `private` members behave: **only the class that "owns" them can touch them**.

## 1.3 Default Visibility Convention (Critical for KTU)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Examiner's Highlight — Default Access Behavior:**
> - In **C++** (using `class` keyword): The **default** access specifier is **`private`**.
> - In **C++** (using `struct` keyword): The **default** access specifier is **`public`**.
> - In **Java**: There is **no default**; every member must be explicitly declared. However, the convention and best practice still emphasizes `private` for data hiding.

This default behavior is a frequent **2-mark question** in KTU module tests. Misremembering `struct`'s default as `private` is a common student error.
