# 3. STEP-BY-STEP ANALYTICAL WALKTHROUGH

This section demonstrates, with exhaustive code and a corresponding **access-control derivation matrix**, exactly how `private` enforces its rules.

## 3.1 Canonical C++ Demonstration

```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class BankAccount {
private:        // ──── Visibility Region 1: HIGHEST RESTRICTION ────
    double balance;        // private data member
    void logTransaction()  // private helper function
    {
        cout << "[LOG] Transaction recorded.\n";
    }

public:         // ──── Visibility Region 2: UNIVERSAL ACCESS ────
    string ownerName;

    BankAccount(string name, double initial) {   // Constructor
        ownerName = name;
        balance = initial;        // ✅ ALLOWED: same class access
    }

    void deposit(double amount) {
        if (amount > 0) {
            balance += amount;    // ✅ ALLOWED: same class
            logTransaction();     // ✅ ALLOWED: same class
        }
    }

    double getBalance() {         // Public getter (controlled window)
        return balance;           // ✅ ALLOWED: same class
    }
};

class SavingsAccount : public BankAccount {
public:
    SavingsAccount(string name, double bal) : BankAccount(name, bal) {}

    void showInheritedInfo() {
        cout << "Owner: " << ownerName << "\n";   // ✅ public member — OK
        // cout << balance;     // ❌ COMPILE ERROR: 'balance' is private in base
    }
};

int main() {
    BankAccount acc("Alice", 5000.0);

    cout << acc.ownerName << "\n";          // ✅ public — OK
    // cout << acc.balance;                // ❌ COMPILE ERROR
    // acc.logTransaction();               // ❌ COMPILE ERROR

    acc.deposit(1500.0);                    // ✅ public method — OK
    cout << "Balance: " << acc.getBalance();// ✅ public getter — OK
    return 0;
}
```

## 3.2 Analytical Derivation — The Access Decision Algorithm

For every access request to a class member $M$ by an entity $E$, the compiler applies the following deterministic decision function:

$$
\text{Access}(E, M) = \begin{cases}
\text{GRANTED} & \text{if } E \in \text{SameClass}(M) \;\lor\; E \in \text{Friends}(M) \\
\text{GRANTED} & \text{if } M.\text{visibility} = \text{public} \\
\text{GRANTED} & \text{if } M.\text{visibility} = \text{protected} \;\land\; E \in \text{DerivedClasses}(\text{Owner}(M)) \\
\text{DENIED} & \text{otherwise (compile-time error)}
\end{cases}
$$

Where:
- $\text{SameClass}(M)$ = the class that lexically declares $M$.
- $\text{Friends}(M)$ = the set of entities declared `friend` inside the owning class.
- $\text{DerivedClasses}(C)$ = the set of all transitively derived classes of $C$.

## 3.3 Step-by-Step Evaluation of Each Access Attempt

We now trace each line of the code above through the access decision algorithm.

**Step 1 — `balance = initial;` inside `BankAccount` constructor:**

$$
\text{Access}(\text{BankAccount::BankAccount},\; \text{balance}) \;\Rightarrow\; E \in \text{SameClass}(\text{balance}) = \text{GRANTED}
$$

**Step 2 — `cout << acc.balance;` inside `main()`:**

$$
\text{Access}(\text{main},\; \text{balance}) \;\Rightarrow\; \text{main} \notin \text{SameClass},\; \text{main} \notin \text{Friends},\; \text{balance}.\text{visibility} = \text{private} \;\Rightarrow\; \text{DENIED}
$$

**Step 3 — `cout << balance;` inside `SavingsAccount::showInheritedInfo`:**

$$
\text{Access}(\text{SavingsAccount},\; \text{balance}) \;\Rightarrow\; \text{SavingsAccount} \notin \text{SameClass}(\text{BankAccount}),\; \text{SavingsAccount} \notin \text{Friends},\; \text{balance}.\text{visibility} = \text{private} \;\Rightarrow\; \text{DENIED}
$$

> **Note:** Even though `SavingsAccount` **inherits** from `BankAccount`, inheritance does **not** override the `private` visibility. This is a critical, exam-favorite distinction.

**Step 4 — `cout << acc.ownerName;` inside `main()`:**

$$
\text{Access}(\text{main},\; \text{ownerName}) \;\Rightarrow\; \text{ownerName}.\text{visibility} = \text{public} \;\Rightarrow\; \text{GRANTED}
$$

## 3.4 The Controlled-Access Pattern (Getter / Setter)

Since direct access is denied, the canonical KTU-mandated solution is the **public accessor/mutator** pair:

$$
\text{Class State} \;\xrightarrow{\text{private field } X}\; \text{public getter: } \texttt{T getX()} \;\;\&\;\; \text{public setter: } \texttt{void setX(T val)}
$$

The setter typically includes a **validation guard**:

$$
\text{setX}(v) = \begin{cases}
\text{Assign } X \leftarrow v & \text{if } \text{isValid}(v) = \text{true} \\
\text{Reject (or throw)} & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
$$

This enforces the class **invariant** $\mathcal{I}(X)$, which is the mathematical/logical condition that all valid states of the object must satisfy (e.g., $X \geq 0$ for a bank balance).
