## PART A — 3-Mark Conceptual Questions

### **Q1. [KTU University Exam — May 2024]**
*Define the `private` access specifier in C++. Can a member function of a derived class access a `private` member of the base class? Justify your answer.*

**Model Answer (3 marks):**
The `private` access specifier in C++ restricts the visibility of class members to the class in which they are declared. A `private` member can be accessed **only** by the member functions and `friend` functions/classes of that same class.
**No**, a derived class **cannot** access a `private` member of the base class, even though it inherits from it. Private members are *inherited* (occupy memory in the derived object) but remain inaccessible directly. The derived class must access them through the base's `public` or `protected` interface. *(3 marks — 1 for definition, 1 for the negative answer, 1 for the inheritance distinction).*

### **Q2. [KTU University Exam — Dec 2023]**
*Differentiate between the default access specifier in a `class` and a `struct` in C++. Why is this distinction important?*

**Model Answer (3 marks):**
In C++, members of a `class` are **`private` by default**, whereas members of a `struct` are **`public` by default**. This distinction is important because it reflects the intended use: `class` is meant for **encapsulated, data-hiding-oriented designs** (OOP), while `struct` is a legacy C-compatible aggregate typically used for **plain data groupings** without strict encapsulation. Misusing them can lead to unintended public exposure of internal state. *(3 marks).*

---

