### **Question A (14 Marks) — [KTU University Exam — May 2024, Adapted]**

**(a)** Define the three access specifiers in C++: `private`, `protected`, and `public`. Construct a class `Employee` with the following design: a `private` member `salary` (double), a `private` helper function `validateSalary(double)`, a `public` member `name` (string), a `public` setter `setSalary(double)` that uses the validator and rejects negative values, and a `public` getter `getSalary()`. Demonstrate the class in `main()`.  **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Explain with a suitable C++ program how `private` members of a base class are **not** directly accessible in a derived class. Show the correct way to access them using a `public` member function of the base class.  **(7 marks)**

