### **Question B (14 Marks) — [KTU University Exam — Dec 2023, Adapted]**

**(a)** What is **data hiding**? How is it achieved in C++ using the `private` specifier? Write a C++ class `Thermometer` with a `private` member `celsius` (double), and `public` methods `setCelsius(double)` (rejecting values below **$-273.15$** °C, the absolute zero) and `getCelsius()`.  **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Discuss the role of the `friend` function as a **deliberate exception** to the `private` access rule. Provide a C++ program where a non-member function `compareAccounts(BankAccount, BankAccount)` accesses the `private` `balance` of two `BankAccount` objects to determine which has a higher balance.  **(7 marks)**

---

#### Model Solution for Q.B(a):

**Conceptual Answer (3 marks):** Data hiding is the OOP principle of restricting direct external access to an object's internal state, preventing accidental or malicious corruption of data. It is achieved in C++ by declaring data members as `private`, forcing all interaction to occur through `public` member functions (the interface). This enforces **invariants** and enables **future implementation changes** without affecting client code.

**Code (4 marks):**

```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Thermometer {
private:
    double celsius;                                    // (1 mark)
    const double ABSOLUTE_ZERO = -273.15;              // (1 mark)

public:
    void setCelsius(double t) {                        // (1 mark)
        if (t >= ABSOLUTE_ZERO) {
            celsius = t;
            cout << "Set to " << t << " °C.\n";
        } else {
            cout << "Error: Below absolute zero!\n";
        }
    }
    double getCelsius() { return celsius; }            // (1 mark)
};
```

#### Model Solution for Q.B(b):

```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class BankAccount {
private:
    double balance;
public:
    BankAccount(double b) : balance(b) {}
    friend void compareAccounts(BankAccount, BankAccount); // (2 marks)
};

void compareAccounts(BankAccount a1, BankAccount a2) {     // (3 marks)
    if (a1.balance > a2.balance)        // ✅ friend access to private
        cout << "Account 1 has more.\n";
    else if (a2.balance > a1.balance)
        cout << "Account 2 has more.\n";
    else
        cout << "Equal balances.\n";
}

int main() {
    BankAccount acc1(5000), acc2(7500);
    compareAccounts(acc1, acc2);          // Output: Account 2 has more.
    return 0;
}
```

**Explanation (2 marks):** The `friend` keyword, declared *inside* the class, grants the external function `compareAccounts` explicit, audited access to the `private` member `balance`. This is the **only** way a non-member function can access `private` data. It must be used sparingly and only when there is a genuine design need (e.g., operator overloading, tightly coupled helper functions).

---

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning — Common Pitfalls:**
> 1. **Mark Loss Trap #1:** Writing `private:` *after* `public:` and then assuming all earlier members are also `private`. Visibility specifiers in C++ apply **only to members declared after them, until the next specifier**. Order matters.
> 2. **Mark Loss Trap #2:** Claiming that `private` members are *not inherited*. They **are** inherited (they occupy memory in the derived object) — they are simply **not accessible** by name in the derived class.
> 3. **Mark Loss Trap #3:** Forgetting to demonstrate the **compile-time error** (e.g., commenting out the illegal access and noting the error). KTU examiners reward the explicit demonstration of the denial.
> 4. **Mark Loss Trap #4:** Writing setters **without validation**. The whole point of the `private`/`public` split is to **enforce invariants at the boundary**. A setter that blindly assigns is a half-implementation.
> 5. **Mark Loss Trap #5:** Confusing `protected` with `private` in inheritance scenarios. Remember: `protected` = same class + derived class; `private` = same class **only**.

---

## TOPIC RECAP & RAPID-REVISION CHECKLIST

- **Definition:** `private` restricts member access to **the declaring class only** (plus `friend` entities).
- **Default in C++ `class`:** `private`. **Default in C++ `struct`:** `public`. **In Java:** No default — must be explicit.
- **Access allowed to:** Own class's member functions, `friend` functions, `friend` classes.
- **Access denied to:** Derived classes (even with `public`/`protected` inheritance), objects of the same class (from outside), unrelated external code.
- **Inheritance behavior:** `private` members **are inherited** (occupy memory) but **cannot be accessed by name** in the derived class. Access must go through the base's `public`/`protected` interface.
- **Encapsulation role:** `private` is the **mechanism**; **encapsulation** is the **principle** it implements. `private` hides data; `public` methods expose a controlled, validated interface.
- **Canonical Pattern:** `private` data + `public` getter/setter (with validation) = the textbook KTU answer.
- **Friend function:** The single, explicit, audit-friendly loophole to the `private` rule. Use sparingly.
- **Keyword context:** The `private` keyword in C++ is a **statement**, not a modifier attached to a single member — it sets the visibility of *all members declared after it* until the next access specifier.
- **Compile-time enforcement:** Violations of `private` are caught at **compile time** — no runtime overhead, no security loopholes via raw memory in well-typed code.
- **UML notation:** Denoted by a leading `-` (minus sign) before the member name in class diagrams.
- **Engineering mantra for exams:** *"If it's not part of the object's public contract, make it `private`."*
