# 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Academic Definition

In the context of **Java Exception Handling (KTU 2024 - OOP Module 3)**, a **Multiple Catch Clause** is a mechanism that allows a single `try` block to be followed by **two or more `catch` handlers**, where each handler is designed to catch and process a *distinct type of exception* (subclass of `java.lang.Throwable`).

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Syllabus Definition:** *"Multiple catch blocks can be used to handle different types of exceptions thrown from a try block. The catch blocks are examined in sequence, and the first one whose parameter type matches the thrown exception (or its superclass) is executed. Only one catch block is executed per exception."*

The structural grammar in Java is:

```java
try {
    // Protected code that may throw multiple exception types
} catch (ExceptionType1 identifier1) {
    // Handler for ExceptionType1
} catch (ExceptionType2 identifier2) {
    // Handler for ExceptionType2
} catch (ExceptionTypeN identifierN) {
    // Handler for ExceptionTypeN
}
```

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy / Intuition

> [!NOTE]
> **Analogy: The Hospital Triage System**
> Imagine a hospital emergency room with **multiple specialized doctors** waiting in a queue:
> - A **Cardiologist** (catches heart-related issues)
> - A **Neurologist** (catches brain-related issues)
> - A **General Physician** (catches everything else)
>
> When a patient arrives (`try` block encounters a problem), the **triage nurse** examines the patient and routes them to the **first applicable doctor** in the queue. The patient does NOT visit all doctors — only the **first match** in the ordered list. This is exactly how Java's multiple catch clauses work: the JVM examines catch blocks in **top-to-bottom order** and routes the thrown exception to the **first matching catch block**.

## 1.3 Core Highlights

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Three Golden Rules of Multiple Catch Clauses:**
> 1. **Sequential Evaluation:** Catch blocks are checked in the order they appear (top to bottom).
> 2. **Single Execution:** Only **one** catch block executes per thrown exception.
> 3. **Specificity Rule:** More specific (subclass) exceptions must be caught **before** more general (superclass) exceptions. Otherwise, a **compile-time error** occurs due to *unreachable code*.

## 1.4 Key Terminology

| Term | Standard Definition |
|------|---------------------|
| **Exception** | An event that disrupts the normal flow of program execution (subclass of `Throwable`) |
| **Catch Block** | A handler that intercepts a thrown exception of a matching type |
| **Unreachable Code** | Code that the compiler determines can never be executed (e.g., `catch(Exception e)` before `catch(IOException e)`) |
| **Multi-Catch (Java 7+)** | A single catch block that handles multiple unrelated exception types using the `\|` operator |
| **Exception Hierarchy** | The inheritance tree rooted at `java.lang.Throwable` |

