- ✅ **Multiple catch clauses** allow a single `try` block to handle **multiple exception types** through separate handlers.
- ✅ Catch blocks are evaluated **top to bottom**, and the **first matching** block is executed.
- ✅ Only **one catch block** executes per exception — the rest are skipped.
- ✅ **Specific (subclass) exceptions must come BEFORE general (superclass) exceptions.**
- ✅ Violating the order rule causes a **compile-time unreachable catch block error**.
- ✅ **Java 7 multi-catch** uses the `|` operator: `catch(Type1 | Type2 e)` to consolidate similar handling.
- ✅ In a multi-catch, the exception variable `e` is **implicitly final** and cannot be reassigned.
- ✅ Multi-catch alternatives **must not have an inheritance relationship** with each other.
- ✅ If no catch block matches, the exception **propagates to the calling method** (unwinds the call stack).
- ✅ `Throwable` is the **root** of the Java exception hierarchy; `Exception` and `Error` are its direct subclasses.
- ✅ `Error` (e.g., `OutOfMemoryError`) is **NOT** caught by `catch(Exception e)` — it requires `catch(Throwable t)` or `catch(Error e)`.
- ✅ **Checked exceptions** (e.g., `IOException`, `SQLException`) require either handling or `throws` declaration; **unchecked** (RuntimeException subclasses) do not.
- ✅ Common runtime exceptions tested in KTU: `ArithmeticException`, `NullPointerException`, `ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException`, `NumberFormatException`, `ClassCastException`.
- ✅ Re-throwing (`throw e;` inside a catch) is used to add context or propagate to upper layers in n-tier architectures.

