# Module 4 — Model View Controller (MVC)

## 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 Formal Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Model View Controller (MVC)** is a **software architectural design pattern** that separates an application into **three interconnected components**: the **Model**, the **View**, and the **Controller**. The pattern is used to isolate the **business logic (domain)** from the **user interface (presentation)**, thereby promoting **separation of concerns**, **modularity**, **reusability**, and **easier maintainability** of Object-Oriented systems.

In the KTU 2024 OOP context, MVC is taught as a **structural design pattern** (one of the Gang-of-Four pattern categories) that demonstrates how multiple objects can collaborate while keeping responsibilities cleanly partitioned. It is also classified as a **compound pattern** because it brings together several other patterns (Strategy, Observer, Composite) to fulfil its role.

| Component | Primary Responsibility | OOP Mapping |
|---|---|---|
| **Model** | Encapsulates application data + business rules; notifies observers of state changes | Plain Old Java Object (POJO) / Domain class |
| **View** | Renders the Model into a UI; passive, requests updates from Model | Swing/JSP/HTML template class |
| **Controller** | Interprets user actions, manipulates Model, selects the next View | Servlet / Event-handler class |

### 1.2 Intuitive Analogy — The Restaurant

> [!NOTE]
> **Real-World Analogy:** Think of MVC as a **restaurant**.
> - **Customer (User)** places an order → input goes to the **Waiter (Controller)**.
> - The **Waiter (Controller)** does not cook; he carries the order to the **Kitchen (Model)**.
> - The **Kitchen (Model)** prepares the data (food) and notifies the Waiter when ready.
> - The **Waiter (Controller)** then decides which **Table Presentation (View)** gets the dish.
> - The **Customer (User)** only ever sees the plated View — never the raw Model.

This is precisely how MVC works: the **User** never touches the **Model** directly; everything passes through the **Controller**, and what is rendered is the **View**.

### 1.3 Why MVC? — The "Why" Question

- **Decoupling** → changing the View does not affect Model code.
- **Parallel Development** → a UI designer and a backend developer can work simultaneously.
- **Testability** → Models can be unit-tested without instantiating a UI.
- **Multiple Views** → the same Model can be displayed as HTML, JSON, or PDF without rewriting business logic.

