# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 The Three Components — Operational Breakdown

### 2.1.1 The Model
- Holds the **state** of the application (data fields, collections).
- Contains the **business rules**: validation, persistence calls, calculations.
- **Notifies** the View/Controller when its state changes (Observer pattern).
- Has **no knowledge** of the View or Controller — it is purely a domain object.

### 2.1.2 The View
- The **presentation layer**.
- Displays data pulled from the Model.
- Is **passive** — it does not perform business logic.
- Registers itself as a **listener** to the Model to receive update notifications.
- A single Model can have **multiple Views** (e.g., bar chart + table showing the same dataset).

### 2.1.3 The Controller
- The **mediator** between Model and View.
- Receives user **input events** (button clicks, form submissions, HTTP requests).
- Translates input into **method calls on the Model**.
- Decides **which View** to render next based on the result.
- Holds **references** to both Model and View (composition).

## 2.2 The Interaction Rules (Bulleted Logic Steps)

1. The **User** interacts with the **View** (clicks a button, submits a form).
2. The **View** forwards the event to the **Controller** (delegate / listener registration).
3. The **Controller** updates the **Model** (calls a mutator method).
4. The **Model** changes its internal state and **fires a notification** to all registered listeners.
5. The **View** (acting as a listener) receives the notification and **re-renders itself** by querying the Model.
6. The **Controller** may also explicitly select a different View to display.

## 2.3 Communication Patterns Used Inside MVC

| Communication Path | Pattern Used | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| Model → View | **Observer** | Notify of state changes |
| View → Controller | **Strategy** | View holds a reference to a Controller strategy |
| Controller → Model | **Direct call / Façade** | Mutate state |
| View composition | **Composite** | Build nested UI trees |

## 2.4 KTU High-Yield Formula / Cheat Sheet

> [!NOTE]
> The "formulas" for a design-pattern topic are its **classification rules, role signatures, and coupling rules**. Memorize this table verbatim for ESE.

| Property | Model | View | Controller |
|---|---|---|---|
| Knows about | Itself only | Model | Model + View |
| Knows about View? | **NO** | Itself | **YES** |
| Knows about Controller? | **NO** | **YES** (indirectly) | Itself |
| Can have multiple instances? | **1 logical Model** | **Yes (many)** | **Yes (many)** |
| Notification responsibility | Sends change events | Receives events | Forwards user events |
| Keyword in Java | `addObserver`, `setChanged` | `update()` from Observer | `actionPerformed()` |
| Typical base class | `Observable` | `JFrame / JPanel` | Custom `Controller` |

**Coupling Rule (critical for KTU):**
$$
\text{Coupling}(M, V) \;=\; 0 \qquad \text{Model must NEVER import View classes}
$$
$$
\text{Coupling}(V, C) \;=\; 1 \qquad \text{View registers with Controller via interface}
$$
$$
\text{Coupling}(C, M) \;=\; 1 \qquad \text{Controller calls Model public API}
$$

## 2.5 Real-World Engineering Utility

- **Web frameworks** → Ruby on Rails, Django, Spring MVC, ASP.NET MVC.
- **Desktop GUI** → Java Swing, JavaFX, .NET WinForms.
- **Mobile development** → iOS UIKit, Android (loose MVC / MVVM hybrid).
- **Enterprise systems** → Any large banking/ERP system uses MVC to allow independent UI swaps.

