# 3. Step-by-Step Derivation & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Exhaustive Worked Example — Java Swing Student Records

> [!NOTE]
> The following derivation walks through **every class, every reference, and every method call** to build a complete MVC application. Each step is enumerated so you can reproduce it in the KTU lab record and ESE answer scripts.

### Step 1 — Identify the Domain Entity

The application will manage a `Student` with three fields: `name`, `rollNo`, `grade`. This is the **Model**.

```java
// ===== MODEL =====
public class Student {
    private String name;
    private String rollNo;
    private String grade;

    public Student(String name, String rollNo, String grade) {
        this.name   = name;
        this.rollNo = rollNo;
        this.grade  = grade;
    }
    // getters
    public String getName()   { return name;   }
    public String getRollNo() { return rollNo; }
    public String getGrade()  { return grade;  }

    // setters (mutators) — these are the only way Controller can change Model state
    public void setName(String name)   { this.name  = name;  }
    public void setGrade(String grade) { this.grade = grade; }
}
```

### Step 2 — Create the View (Swing UI)

The View is a `JFrame` that displays the data and exposes **event registration hooks** for the Controller. It does NOT contain business logic.

```java
// ===== VIEW =====
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.*;
public class StudentView extends JFrame {
    private JTextField txtName    = new JTextField(15);
    private JTextField txtRollNo  = new JTextField(15);
    private JTextField txtGrade   = new JTextField(15);
    private JButton    btnSave    = new JButton("Save");
    private JButton    btnClear   = new JButton("Clear");

    public StudentView() {
        setTitle("Student MVC Demo");
        setLayout(new GridLayout(4, 2, 5, 5));
        add(new JLabel("Name:"));    add(txtName);
        add(new JLabel("Roll No:")); add(txtRollNo);
        add(new JLabel("Grade:"));   add(txtGrade);
        add(btnSave);                add(btnClear);
        pack(); setDefaultCloseOperation(EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
    }

    // Setters called by Controller after Model changes
    public void setName(String s)   { txtName.setText(s);  }
    public void setRollNo(String s) { txtRollNo.setText(s);}
    public void setGrade(String s)  { txtGrade.setText(s); }

    // Getters called by Controller when user types
    public String getName()         { return txtName.getText();  }
    public String getRollNo()       { return txtRollNo.getText();}
    public String getGrade()        { return txtGrade.getText(); }

    // Hooks so the Controller can register its listeners
    public JButton getSaveButton()  { return btnSave; }
    public JButton getClearButton() { return btnClear; }
}
```

### Step 3 — Build the Controller

The Controller holds **references** to both the Model and the View. It listens to View events and pushes data into the Model.

```java
// ===== CONTROLLER =====
import java.awt.event.*;
public class StudentController {
    private Student    model;   // composition
    private StudentView view;    // composition

    public StudentController(Student m, StudentView v) {
        this.model = m;
        this.view  = v;

        // Wire View events to Controller methods
        this.view.getSaveButton().addActionListener(new ActionListener() {
            public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) { saveAction(); }
        });
        this.view.getClearButton().addActionListener(new ActionListener() {
            public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) { clearAction(); }
        });

        // Initial sync of View from Model
        this.view.setName(model.getName());
        this.view.setRollNo(model.getRollNo());
        this.view.setGrade(model.getGrade());
    }

    private void saveAction() {
        // Read from View, write to Model
        model.setName(view.getName());
        model.setGrade(view.getGrade());
        System.out.println("Saved: " + model.getName() + ", Grade " + model.getGrade());
    }

    private void clearAction() {
        view.setName("");
        view.setGrade("");
    }
}
```

### Step 4 — Main / Driver Class

```java
// ===== DRIVER =====
public class MVCDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Student       model  = new Student("Arjun", "S101", "A");
        StudentView   view   = new StudentView();
        StudentController ctrl = new StudentController(model, view);
        view.setVisible(true);
    }
}
```

### Step 5 — Trace the Request Flow (the "Why" of MVC)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> When the user clicks **Save**, the following **causal chain** fires — write this in your exam:

1. `JButton` raises an `ActionEvent`.
2. The registered `ActionListener` (an **anonymous inner class** inside Controller) receives it.
3. Controller invokes `saveAction()`.
4. `saveAction()` reads `txtName` and `txtGrade` **from the View** via getters.
5. Controller writes those values **into the Model** via `setName()` / `setGrade()`.
6. Model state is mutated.
7. If the Model used `java.util.Observable`, it would call `setChanged()` + `notifyObservers()`; here we only print to console.
8. Controller returns — flow ends.

## 3.2 Analytical Matrix — Responsibilities vs Classes

| Responsibility | Student (Model) | StudentView (View) | StudentController (Controller) |
|---|:---:|:---:|:---:|
| Hold student data | **YES** | NO | NO |
| Render UI components | NO | **YES** | NO |
| Listen to UI events | NO | Indirectly (via forwarding) | **YES** |
| Validate input | **YES** (business rule) | NO | Optional (format check) |
| Mutate Model state | Own methods only | NO | **YES** (via setters) |
| Decide next View | NO | NO | **YES** |
| Persist to DB | **YES** (DAO call) | NO | NO |

## 3.3 Mathematical / Logical Notation of MVC Flow

Let:
- $U$ = User input event
- $C$ = Controller
- $M$ = Model
- $V$ = View
- $\mu$ = mutation function
- $\rho$ = render function
- $\nu$ = notification function

The full request cycle can be expressed as:

$$
U \;\xrightarrow{\text{event}}\; C \;\xrightarrow{\mu}\; M \;\xrightarrow{\nu}\; V \;\xrightarrow{\rho}\; \text{Display}
$$

Or more formally:

$$
\text{Display}_{t+1} \;=\; \rho\bigl(V,\; M\bigl(\mu(C,\, U_t)\bigr)\bigr)
$$

This compact equation says: the next display is the **render of the View**, applied to the **Model**, which has been **mutated** by the **Controller** in response to the **User event at time $t$**. This is the mathematical essence of MVC and is a **bonus answer** in KTU ESE if a student writes it.

