# SECTION 1: Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 JTextField — Formal KTU Definition

**JTextField** is a lightweight Swing component (`javax.swing.JTextField`) that allows the user to **edit a single line of unformatted text**. It is the Swing successor to the legacy AWT `TextField` class and inherits from `javax.swing.JTextComponent`.

In KTU 2024 OOP terminology, JTextField is treated as a concrete subclass within the **Swing Component Hierarchy**:
```
java.lang.Object
  └── java.awt.Component
        └── java.awt.Container
              └── javax.swing.JComponent
                    └── javax.swing.text.JTextComponent
                              └── javax.swing.JTextField
```

### Conceptual Analogy — The "Single-Line Sticky Note"
Imagine a **single blank line on a paper form** — that's a JTextField. You can type into it, select text inside it, copy/paste, clear it, or replace its contents programmatically. Unlike a `JTextArea` (which behaves like a notebook page with many lines), a `JTextField` strictly enforces **one line of text**. If you press `Enter`, the text does *not* wrap to a new line — instead, an `ActionEvent` is fired (similar to clicking a button), which makes it perfect for **login forms, search bars, and data-entry dialogs**.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Syllabus Highlight:** JTextField is one of the **text-input controls** expected in GUI programming questions. You must know its constructors, key methods (`setText()`, `getText()`, `setEditable()`), and how to attach an `ActionListener`.

### Key Architectural Properties of JTextField

| Property | Description | Default Value |
|---|---|---|
| **Editable** | Whether the user can type into the field | `true` |
| **Horizontal Alignment** | LEFT, CENTER, RIGHT, LEADING, TRAILING | `LEADING` |
| **Columns** | Preferred width in character columns | `0` |
| **Text** | The current string content | `""` (empty) |
| **Echo Char** | Character used to mask input (passwords) | `0` (no mask) |

