# SECTION 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet

## 2.1 JTextField — Theoretical Breakdown

### 2.1.1 Constructors (KTU-Favorite)

The `JTextField` class provides **four overloaded constructors**:

| Constructor | Purpose | Example |
|---|---|---|
| `JTextField()` | Creates an empty field with default columns (0). | `new JTextField();` |
| `JTextField(String text)` | Creates a field pre-populated with text. | `new JTextField("Enter name");` |
| `JTextField(int columns)` | Creates an empty field with preferred width. | `new JTextField(15);` |
| `JTextField(String text, int columns)` | Pre-populated text **and** width. | `new JTextField("Admin", 10);` |

### 2.1.2 Key Methods (The "Must-Know" Set)

| Method | Returns | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `getText()` | `String` | Returns current contents of the field. |
| `setText(String t)` | `void` | Replaces the field's contents. |
| `getColumns()` | `int` | Returns preferred column count. |
| `setColumns(int c)` | `void` | Sets preferred column count. |
| `setEditable(boolean b)` | `void` | `true` = editable, `false` = read-only. |
| `isEditable()` | `boolean` | Returns editable status. |
| `setHorizontalAlignment(int a)` | `void` | Aligns text (LEFT, CENTER, RIGHT). |
| `setEchoChar(char c)` | `void` | Masks input (used for passwords). |
| `addActionListener(ActionListener l)` | `void` | Registers a listener for `Enter` key. |
| `requestFocus()` | `void` | Sets keyboard focus to the field. |

### 2.1.3 Why Use JTextField Over AWT `TextField`?

1. **Pluggable Look & Feel (PLAF)** — JTextField automatically adopts the host OS theme.
2. **Icon and Tooltip support** — inherited from `JComponent`.
3. **Document model integration** — connects to the powerful `javax.swing.text.Document` API for validation, undo/redo.
4. **Accessibility (JAAPI)** — screen readers can interpret Swing components better.
5. **Double buffering** — eliminates flickering during repaints.

### 2.1.4 Event Handling — The `ActionEvent` Behavior

When the user presses the **Enter key** inside a JTextField, the component fires an `ActionEvent`. This is registered via:

```java
textField.addActionListener(e -> {
    String input = textField.getText();
    System.out.println("User entered: " + input);
});
```

> [!TIP]
> **Engineering Utility:** In a login form, the user types their password and hits Enter — the JTextField's ActionListener can trigger the login button's action without needing a separate `JButton.addActionListener()` call. This is called **"Enter key submission"** and is standard in production UIs.

