## 2.2 JDBC Architecture — The 4-Layer Model

JDBC's architecture is best understood as **four logical layers**, each with a specific responsibility:

### Layer 1 — Java Application Layer
The user's Java program that calls JDBC API methods. This layer is **100% database-agnostic**.

### Layer 2 — JDBC API Layer
The standardized set of **interfaces and classes** in `java.sql` and `javax.sql`. Key members:
- `DriverManager` — entry point service.
- `Connection` — represents a session with a DB.
- `Statement`, `PreparedStatement`, `CallableStatement` — SQL execution.
- `ResultSet` — represents query results.
- `SQLException` — checked exception for DB errors.

> [!NOTE]
> **Critical KTU Insight:** Most JDBC API members are **interfaces**, not concrete classes. The actual implementation is provided by the **JDBC Driver** (vendor-supplied). This is the **"interface-based, implementation-injected"** pattern — a perfect OOP principle in action!

### Layer 3 — JDBC Driver Manager Layer
`java.sql.DriverManager` is a **service-locator class** that:
1. Maintains a registry of available drivers loaded via the service-provider mechanism (`META-INF/services/java.sql.Driver`).
2. Accepts a JDBC URL (`jdbc:<subprotocol>:<subname>`).
3. Iterates through registered drivers and selects the one that recognizes the URL.
4. Returns a `Connection` object.

### Layer 4 — JDBC Driver Layer (Vendor-Specific)
Translates JDBC calls into the **native protocol** of the target DBMS. Four driver types exist:

| Type | Name | Mechanism | Pure Java? |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Type 1** | JDBC-ODBC Bridge | Translates JDBC → ODBC → DB | No (needs ODBC) |
| **Type 2** | Native-API Driver | Uses vendor client libraries (e.g., Oracle OCI) | Partially |
| **Type 3** | Network Protocol Driver | Sends requests to a middleware server | Yes |
| **Type 4** | Thin Driver (Pure Java) | Direct DB protocol over TCP/IP | **Yes** ✅ |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Exam Favorite:** Type 4 (Pure Java / Thin Driver) is the **industry standard** today. Examples: `com.mysql.cj.jdbc.Driver` (MySQL Connector/J), `oracle.jdbc.driver.OracleDriver`, `org.postgresql.Driver`.

### Layer 5 — Database Layer
The actual RDBMS server (MySQL, Oracle, PostgreSQL, SQLite, MS SQL Server).

---

## 2.3 The Five Mandatory Steps of Any JDBC Program (KTU Killer Cheat Sheet)

These five steps are **guaranteed to appear** in KTU board exams:

| Step | Method | Description |
|---|---|---|
| **1. Load Driver** | `Class.forName("driver.class.name")` | Loads the vendor driver into memory. *(Optional in JDBC 4.0+ due to auto-loading via service provider.)* |
| **2. Establish Connection** | `DriverManager.getConnection(url, user, pwd)` | Opens a session with the DB; returns `Connection`. |
| **3. Create Statement** | `conn.createStatement()` or `conn.prepareStatement(sql)` | Returns a SQL execution object. |
| **4. Execute Query / Update** | `stmt.executeQuery(sql)` (SELECT) or `stmt.executeUpdate(sql)` (INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE) | Returns `ResultSet` (for SELECT) or `int` row count (for DML). |
| **5. Close Connection** | `conn.close()` | Releases DB resources — **must always be in a `finally` block**. |

### JDBC URL Format Cheat Sheet

| Database | JDBC URL Pattern |
|---|---|
| **MySQL** | `jdbc:mysql://hostname:3306/dbname` |
| **Oracle (SID)** | `jdbc:oracle:thin:@hostname:1521:SID` |
| **Oracle (Service)** | `jdbc:oracle:thin:@hostname:1521/service` |
| **PostgreSQL** | `jdbc:postgresql://hostname:5432/dbname` |
| **SQL Server** | `jdbc:sqlserver://hostname:1433;databaseName=dbname` |
| **SQLite** | `jdbc:sqlite:filename.db` |

### Core Interfaces vs. Classes Summary

| Component | Type | Package |
|---|---|---|
| `DriverManager` | **Class** (concrete) | `java.sql` |
| `Connection` | Interface | `java.sql` |
| `Statement` | Interface | `java.sql` |
| `PreparedStatement` | Interface (extends Statement) | `java.sql` |
| `CallableStatement` | Interface (extends PreparedStatement) | `java.sql` |
| `ResultSet` | Interface | `java.sql` |
| `ResultSetMetaData` | Interface | `java.sql` |
| `DatabaseMetaData` | Interface | `java.sql` |
| `SQLException` | **Class** (checked exception) | `java.sql` |
| `DataSource` | Interface | `javax.sql` |

> [!NOTE]
> **Why Interfaces Dominate JDBC:** This design is the textbook **Strategy + Bridge pattern** in OOP. Your code depends on *abstractions* (interfaces), not *implementations* (driver classes). This is why the same Java program can talk to MySQL or Oracle by simply swapping the driver JAR.
