## 3.1 JTextField — Complete Working Program

### Program 1: Basic JTextField inside a JFrame

```java
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;

public class TextFieldDemo extends JFrame implements ActionListener {

    // 1. DECLARE the components at class level so all methods can access them.
    JTextField nameField, passwordField;
    JLabel nameLabel, passwordLabel, resultLabel;
    JButton submitButton;

    // 2. CONSTRUCTOR — sets up the GUI.
    public TextFieldDemo() {
        setTitle("JTextField Demo - KTU 2024");
        setSize(400, 250);
        setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
        setLayout(new FlowLayout(FlowLayout.CENTER, 15, 15));

        // 3. INITIALIZE components.
        nameLabel = new JLabel("Name:");
        nameField = new JTextField(15);                // 15 columns wide
        nameField.setToolTipText("Enter your full name");

        passwordLabel = new JLabel("Password:");
        passwordField = new JTextField(15);
        passwordField.setEchoChar('*');                 // Mask input

        submitButton = new JButton("Login");
        resultLabel = new JLabel("Awaiting input...");

        // 4. REGISTER event handlers.
        submitButton.addActionListener(this);
        nameField.addActionListener(this);              // Triggers on Enter key
        passwordField.addActionListener(this);

        // 5. ADD components to the frame's content pane.
        add(nameLabel);
        add(nameField);
        add(passwordLabel);
        add(passwordField);
        add(submitButton);
        add(resultLabel);

        setVisible(true);   // MUST be the LAST statement in constructor.
    }

    // 6. EVENT HANDLER — executes when button is clicked or Enter is pressed.
    @Override
    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        String user = nameField.getText();
        String pwd  = new String(passwordField.getText());  // getText() returns String, but masked visually.
        resultLabel.setText("Welcome, " + user + "!");
        nameField.setText("");        // Clear the name field.
        nameField.requestFocus();     // Move cursor back to name field.
    }

    // 7. MAIN method — program entry point.
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new TextFieldDemo();
    }
}
```

### Step-by-Step Analytical Matrix

| Line # | Code Statement | Engineering Logic |
|---|---|---|
| 1–3 | `import` statements | Pull Swing components, AWT layouts, and event classes into scope. |
| 6 | `class TextFieldDemo extends JFrame` | Inheritance — our class *is-a* window. |
| 7 | `implements ActionListener` | Interface implementation — class *can handle* action events. |
| 11–15 | Field declarations | Object composition — we *have-a* text field, label, button. |
| 22 | `new JTextField(15)` | Constructor with column count sets preferred width ≈ 15 character cells. |
| 27 | `setEchoChar('*')` | Defensive programming — passwords should not be visible. |
| 33–35 | `addActionListener(this)` | **Step 1 of Observer Pattern** — register the listener. |
| 42 | `actionPerformed()` | **Step 2 of Observer Pattern** — define callback behavior. |
| 50 | `setVisible(true)` | Without this, the window remains invisible (Swing quirk). |

### Key Learning Outcomes for JTextField

> [!NOTE]
> **What KTU tests you on:**
> 1. Knowing that **JTextField is single-line** (vs. JTextArea which is multi-line).
> 2. Knowing `setEchoChar()` is used for **password masking**.
> 3. Knowing that pressing **Enter** triggers an `ActionEvent`.
> 4. Knowing that `getText()` and `setText()` are the **read/write** methods.

