## PART B — Long Answer Questions (14 Marks Each, Module Internal Choice)

### Question A (14 Marks) — Choice Option 1

> **[KTU University Exam - Sample Model Paper 2024]**
> *Explain JDBC Architecture in detail with a neat diagram. List and explain the different types of JDBC drivers. Write a Java program using JDBC to fetch all records from a `products` table (columns: `pid`, `pname`, `price`) where `price > 500`.*

#### (a) JDBC Architecture and Driver Types — 7 Marks

**JDBC Architecture (4 marks):**

JDBC follows a **4-tier layered architecture**:

1. **Java Application Layer** — The user's Java program. Database-independent.
2. **JDBC API Layer** — Standardized interfaces (`Connection`, `Statement`, `ResultSet`) in `java.sql`.
3. **Driver Manager Layer** — `DriverManager` class acts as a service locator that selects the appropriate driver based on the JDBC URL.
4. **JDBC Driver Layer** — Vendor-specific implementation that converts JDBC calls into DB-native protocol.

**JDBC Driver Types (3 marks):**

| Type | Name | Description | Pure Java? |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Type 1** | JDBC-ODBC Bridge | Translates JDBC → ODBC → DB. Needs ODBC drivers installed. | No |
| **Type 2** | Native-API Driver | Uses vendor client-side libraries (e.g., Oracle OCI). | Partially |
| **Type 3** | Network Protocol Driver | Uses a middleware server that translates JDBC to DB protocol. | Yes |
| **Type 4** | Thin Driver (Pure Java) | Directly converts JDBC calls to DB-specific protocol over TCP/IP. | Yes |

**Type 4 is the industry standard** today (e.g., MySQL Connector/J).

#### (b) Java JDBC Program — 7 Marks

```java
import java.sql.*;

public class ProductFetcher {

    static final String URL  = "jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/shopdb";
    static final String USER = "root";
    static final String PASS = "password123";

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        // try-with-resources auto-closes Connection and Statement.
        try {
            Class.forName("com.mysql.cj.jdbc.Driver");

            try (Connection conn = DriverManager.getConnection(URL, USER, PASS);
                 Statement stmt = conn.createStatement();
                 ResultSet rs = stmt.executeQuery(
                     "SELECT pid, pname, price FROM products WHERE price > 500")) {

                System.out.printf("%-10s %-25s %-10s%n", "PID", "Product Name", "Price");
                System.out.println("--------------------------------------------------");

                while (rs.next()) {
                    int    pid   = rs.getInt("pid");
                    String pname = rs.getString("pname");
                    double price = rs.getDouble("price");
                    System.out.printf("%-10d %-25s %-10.2f%n", pid, pname, price);
                }
            }
        } catch (ClassNotFoundException e) {
            System.err.println("Driver not found: " + e.getMessage());
        } catch (SQLException e) {
            System.err.println("SQL Error: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}
```

**Expected Output:**
```
PID        Product Name              Price
--------------------------------------------------
101        Wireless Mouse            750.00
102        Mechanical Keyboard       1299.50
104        27-inch Monitor           18999.00
```

