> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Pitfalls — Where Students Lose Marks:**
> 1. **Forgetting `Class.forName()`** — Even though optional in JDBC 4.0+, KTU answers that omit it lose a mark. Always include it and add a comment like *"Optional in JDBC 4.0+ due to auto-loading."*
> 2. **Closing `ResultSet` before `Statement`** — Resources must be closed in **reverse order of opening**: `ResultSet → Statement → Connection`.
> 3. **Confusing `Statement.executeQuery()` with `executeUpdate()`** — Query returns `ResultSet`; Update returns `int` row count.
> 4. **Forgetting to set `setVisible(true)`** — The JFrame won't appear, and the examiner thinks your program "doesn't work."
> 5. **Using `TextField` (AWT) instead of `JTextField` (Swing)** — KTU 2024 syllabus explicitly tests Swing components.
> 6. **Not handling `SQLException`** — JDBC code without try-catch will not compile; KTU strictly enforces exception handling.
> 7. **Confusing `setEchoChar` with `setPassword` style masking** — `setEchoChar('*')` is the correct Swing API.
> 8. **Hardcoding credentials in real projects** — While acceptable in exams, KTU awards bonus marks if you mention *"in production, credentials should be externalized via config files or environment variables."*

